## Experiment 2 An introduction to the Telecoms-Trainer 101

Utilizing block diagrams and hands-on measurements, the Emona Telecoms-Trainer 101 is a modular training platform that teaches the fundamental building blocks of analog communication systems. Signals are generated, amplified, added, phase-shifted, and controlled in frequency in real communication systems according to the application.


## OBJECTIVES
1. Familiarize with the Telecoms-Trainer 101 analog modules and their functions.
2. Measure the phase difference between sine and cosine signals using an oscilloscope method.
3. Demonstrate the Buffer module as an amplifier/driver for different signal sources (sine, speech).
4. Investigate how the Adder module gain controls affect output amplitude.

## MATERIALS
1. Emona Telecoms-Trainer 101 (with power pack)
2. Dual-channel oscilloscope (≥ 20 MHz recommended)
3. Two oscilloscope probes/leads (Ch.1 and Ch.2)
4. Patch leads (banana/patch cords as provided by Emona kit)
5. Headphones (stereo) — for Buffer/Speech section AH

## PROCEDURES

1.  Master Signals, Speech and Buffer Modules

      A. Master Signals: Amplitude, Period, Frequency
          1. Set up the oscilloscope (Trigger Source = Ch.1 or INT; Mode = Ch.1).
          2. Connect the Master Signals 2 kHz SINE output to the oscilloscope (Ch.1).
          3. Adjust timebase to view ~2 cycles clearly.
          4. Measure and record:
        Output voltage (peak-to-peak)
           - Period
           - Frequency (calculate using ( f = 1/T ))
           - Output voltage (peak-to-peak)
        Repeat for:
           - 100 kHz SINE
           - 100 kHz COS
       B. Phase Difference: 100 kHz SINE vs 100 kHz COS
          1. Connect 100 kHz SINE to Ch.1 and 100 kHz COS to Ch.2.
          2. Set oscilloscope Mode to DUAL.
          3. Align both traces at midline (use vertical position).
          4. Measure:
                  - Period (one full cycle in divisions)
                  - Horizontal “difference” between waveforms (divisions)
          5. Compute phase difference: [ \phi = difference/period*360^\circ ]
       C. Speech Module Observation
          1. Set oscilloscope Mode to Ch.1 and timebase to around 2 ms/div.
          2. Connect Speech module output to Ch.1.
          3. Speak into the microphone (“one”, “two”, hum, whistle).
          4. Observe waveform shape changes and record qualitative observations.
       D. Buffer Module Test (Headphones)
          1. Turn Buffer Gain fully anti-clockwise.
          2. Plug headphones into Buffer module.
          3. Slowly increase Gain and listen.
          4. Test listening using:
            - Master Signals 2 kHz SINE (audible)
            - Speech output (audible speech waveform)
            - Master Signals 100 kHz SINE (inaudible)

 2. Adder and Phase Shifter Modules
       A. Adder Module: Gain Control and Output
          1. Set Adder input B gain fully anti-clockwise (as specified).
          2. Set Adder input A gain to mid position.
          3. Connect Master Signals 2 kHz SINE to Input A, connect Adder output to Ch.2.
          4. Set oscilloscope Mode to DUAL (Ch.1 = input reference, Ch.2 = output).
          5. Vary Adder gain control and observe amplitude changes.
          6. Measure and record gain for:
            - Input A at max and min gain settings
            - Input B at max and min gain settings
          7. Connect 2 kHz SINE to both inputs and measure new output (summing effect).
       B. Phase Shifter Module: Lead/Lag and Range
          1. Set Phase Change control to 0° position and Phase Adjust to mid.
          2. Connect Master Signals 2 kHz SINE to Phase Shifter input.
          3. Observe input (Ch.1) vs output (Ch.2) in DUAL mode.
          4. Turn Phase Adjust and observe phase shift.
          5. Set Phase Change to 180° and repeat.
          6. Determine if output can:
            - always lead
            - always lag
            - lead or lag depending on setting
          7. Determine if phase shifting up to 360° is possible.
  3. VCO Module
       A. VCO Basic Output Measurements
          1. Set oscilloscope: Trigger Source = Ch.1; Mode = Ch.1.
          2. Set VCO Gain and Frequency Adjust to mid.
          3. Set Range to LO.
          4. Connect VCO SINE output to Ch.1.
          5. Measure output Vpp and record (Table 1).
          6. Turn Frequency Adjust fully anti-clockwise and record minimum frequency.
          7. Turn Frequency Adjust fully clockwise and record maximum frequency.
          8. Switch Range to HI and repeat min/max frequency measurements (Table 2).
       B. Variable DCV → VCO Frequency Control
          1. Set Variable DCV control to mid.
          2. Connect Variable DCV output to VCO input (VCO INPUT).
          3. Observe VCO output while turning VDC clockwise and anti-clockwise.
          4. Record how control voltage affects VCO frequency.

